Confusion Matrix (Document-Category Level)

How to read this matrix

Each document is evaluated across 12 PII categories, producing document × 12 cells total. For each cell, we check: "Does this category actually contain PII?" vs "Did the model detect PII in this category?"

TP True Positive — PII actually exists, and the model correctly detected it. Higher is better.
TN True Negative — No PII exists, and the model correctly ignored it. Higher is better.
FP False Positive — No PII exists, but the model incorrectly flagged it as PII. Lower is better. Users get unnecessary masking/alerts.
FN False Negative — PII actually exists, but the model missed it. Lower is better. This is a privacy risk — sensitive data goes undetected.

Sensitivity (TPR) = TP / (TP + FN) — "Of all real PII, how much did the model catch?" Higher = fewer privacy leaks.

Specificity (TNR) = TN / (TN + FP) — "Of all non-PII, how much did the model correctly leave alone?" Higher = fewer false alarms.

Per-Category Confusion Matrix

Below shows TP/TN/FP/FN per PII category (e.g. Name, Address, SSN...). Categories with high FP are being over-detected (false alarms). Categories with high FN are being missed (privacy risk). Ideally: high TP & TN, zero FP & FN.
